            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/account/security"]""",
            Tags = """["mfa","security"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)\n\nMulti-factor authentication adds an extra layer of security to your QB Engineer account. Instead of relying on your password alone, MFA requires a second verification step — a time-based code from an authenticator app — every time you sign in.\n\n### What Is TOTP?\n\nTOTP stands for Time-based One-Time Password. When you enable MFA, QB Engineer generates a secret key that you register with an authenticator app on your phone. The app uses this key plus the current time to produce a 6-digit code that changes every 30 seconds. When you sign in, you enter your password first, then the current code from your app. Because the code changes constantly and requires your physical device, a stolen password alone is not enough to access your account.\n\n### Supported Authenticator Apps\n\nAny TOTP-compatible authenticator app works with QB Engineer:\n- **Google Authenticator** — simple, widely used\n- **Authy** — supports cloud backup and multi-device sync\n- **Microsoft Authenticator** — integrates with Microsoft accounts\n- **1Password / Bitwarden** — password managers with built-in TOTP support\n\nDuring setup, you scan a QR code with your chosen app, or manually enter the secret key if scanning is not possible.\n\n### Recovery Codes\n\nRecovery codes are one-time-use backup codes that let you sign in if you lose access to your authenticator app (lost phone, factory reset, app deleted). QB Engineer generates a set of codes when you enable MFA, and you can regenerate them at any time from Account > Security.\n\n**Important rules about recovery codes:**\n- Each code can only be used once — after use it is permanently consumed\n- Generating new codes invalidates all previous codes\n- Store them somewhere safe and separate from your phone (printed, in a password manager, or in a secure document)\n- The Security page shows how many unused codes you have remaining\n\n### The Login Flow with MFA\n\n1. Enter your email and password as usual\n2. If MFA is enabled, you see a challenge screen asking for your 6-digit code\n3. Open your authenticator app and enter the current code\n4. Optionally check \"Remember this device\" to skip MFA on trusted devices\n5. If you cannot access your authenticator, click \"Use recovery code\" and enter one of your backup codes\n\n### Registering More Than One Device\n\nYou are not limited to a single authenticator. Once MFA is on, the **Add Device** button (where the Enable button used to be) lets you register a second app — a tablet, a backup phone, or a password manager on another machine. Having two devices means a lost or wiped phone no longer locks you out: you simply authenticate from the other one.\n\nIn the **Registered Devices** list, exactly one device carries a blue **Default** chip. The login challenge is bound to that default device specifically — when you sign in, you enter the current 6-digit code from the default device's authenticator, not from any other registered device. If you cannot reach the default device, your fallback at the challenge screen is a recovery code. Removing a device you no longer trust is a per-row action; if you remove the device that happened to be the default, another registered device takes over as the primary, so the page is never left without a default while any device remains.\n\nA practical setup for a manufacturing environment: register your everyday phone as the default, add your password manager (1Password / Bitwarden) as a second device, and keep your printed recovery codes in a locked drawer. That way a dead battery on the floor doesn't strand you at the login screen.\n\n### Admin-Enforced MFA Policies\n\nAdministrators can require MFA for specific roles (e.g., Admin, Manager). When a policy is enforced:\n- Users in the affected roles see a warning on their Security page: \"Required by organization policy\"\n- The Disable MFA button is hidden — you cannot turn off MFA while the policy applies to your role\n- New users assigned to an enforced role must set up MFA on their next login\n- The Admin > MFA panel shows a compliance table listing all users, their MFA status, device type, and whether their role is enforced\n\n### When to Use MFA\n\n- **Always recommended** for all users to protect against password breaches\n- **Required** when your admin has enforced an MFA policy for your role\n- **Especially important** for Admin and Manager roles that have access to sensitive data, user management, and system settings\n- **Critical** if you access QB Engineer from shared or public computers","sections":[]}"""
        });

