nation":"TOTP codes rotate every 30 seconds. If you entered a code just as it was expiring, it may fail validation. Wait for the next code to appear in your authenticator app and try again."},{"id":"mfa4","text":"You've lost your phone and can't access your authenticator app. How do you sign in to QB Engineer?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You cannot — contact your admin to reset your account"},{"id":"b","text":"On the MFA challenge screen, click 'Use recovery code' and enter one of your saved backup codes","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Use your kiosk PIN instead of the MFA code"},{"id":"d","text":"Wait 24 hours and MFA automatically disables itself"}],"explanation":"Recovery codes are one-time-use backup codes generated when you set up MFA. On the login MFA challenge screen, switch to recovery code entry mode and use one of your saved codes. Each code can only be used once."},{"id":"mfa5","text":"You just generated new recovery codes. What happens to your old recovery codes?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They remain valid alongside the new ones for 30 days"},{"id":"b","text":"All previous recovery codes are immediately invalidated — only the new set works","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Old codes continue working but are marked as deprecated"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — you can have multiple sets of active recovery codes"}],"explanation":"Generating new recovery codes invalidates all previous codes immediately. This is a security measure to ensure only one set of valid codes exists at any time. The dialog warns you about this before generating."},{"id":"mfa6","text":"Your admin has enforced MFA for your role. What changes on your Security page?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing changes — enforcement only affects new users"},{"id":"b","text":"A policy badge appears saying 'Required by organization policy' and the Disable MFA button is hidden","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Your MFA is automatically enabled without any setup needed"},{"id":"d","text":"You receive a one-time email with instructions but can still disable MFA"}],"explanation":"When MFA is enforced by admin policy, your Security page shows a 'Required by organization policy' badge and the Disable MFA button is hidden. You cannot turn off MFA while the policy applies to your role. If MFA is not yet enabled, a warning urges you to set it up."},{"id":"mfa7","text":"As an admin, you want to require MFA for all Manager and Admin users. How do you do this?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Edit each user individually and check 'Require MFA' on their profile"},{"id":"b","text":"Go to Admin > MFA, select Manager and Admin in the 'Required for Roles' multi-select, and click Save","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Enable a global setting that forces MFA for all users regardless of role"},{"id":"d","text":"Send an email notification asking those users to enable MFA voluntarily"}],"explanation":"The Admin > MFA panel has a 'Required for Roles' multi-select dropdown. Select the roles you want to enforce (e.g., Manager, Admin) and click Save. The compliance table below shows which users have MFA enabled and which roles are enforced."},{"id":"mfa8","text":"In the Admin MFA compliance table, a user shows 'Disabled' under MFA Enabled and 'Enforced' under the Enforced column. What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The user has disabled MFA against policy — no action needed"},{"id":"b","text":"The user's role requires MFA but they haven't set it up yet — they'll be prompted on next login","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"There's a system error — enforcement and disabled status can't coexist"},{"id":"d","text":"The user was recently removed from an enforced role"}],"explanation":"When a user's role has MFA enforced but they haven't set it up yet, the compliance table shows Disabled + Enforced. The user will see a warning on their Security page and must complete MFA setup. They cannot bypass this requirement."},{"id":"mfa9","text":"You have two authenticator devices registered. One shows a blue 'Default' chip. What does the Default designation mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It's the only device that can be used — the other is a backup that must be activated first"},{"id":"b","text":"It's the device used first during login challenges — the system prompts for a code from this device before trying others","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"It's the device that was registered first chronologically"},{"id":"d","text":"It receives push notifications while the non-default device requires manual code entry"}],"explanation":"The Default device is the one used first during the login MFA challenge. When you sign in, the system prompts for a code from your default device. You can still use any registered device, but the default is the primary one presented."},{"id":"mfa10","text":"You want to remove an MFA device from your account, but it's your only registered device. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The system prevents removal — you must have at least one device"},{"id":"b","text":"A confirmation dialog warns that removing your only device may lock you out, and you must confirm the deletion","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The device is removed and MFA is automatically disabled"},{"id":"d","text":"The device is removed but a temporary bypass code is emailed to you"}],"explanation":"Clicking the delete icon on your only device opens a danger-severity confirmation dialog warning that you may lose access to your account. If you confirm, the device is removed. You should have recovery codes saved as a backup, or disable MFA entirely if you no longer want it."}]}"""
