            Tags = """["account","security","password","pin"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Your Account Security Page\n\nEverything you control about how you sign in lives on one screen: **Account > Security**. It is laid out as a set of cards. The first card changes your account **password**, the second sets your **kiosk PIN**, and the third manages **two-factor authentication (MFA)**. This article covers the first two — the everyday tasks every user should know. MFA has its own dedicated training.\n\n### Changing Your Account Password\n\nYour password is what you type (together with your email) to sign in to QB Engineer from a browser. Change it from the **Change Password** card whenever you suspect it has been seen, after a shared-credential handoff, or just on a routine cadence.\n\nThe card has three fields:\n- **Current Password** — proves it is really you. If this is wrong, the change is rejected and your password is left unchanged.\n- **New Password** — must be at least **8 characters**. Use something long and unique; a passphrase beats a short complex string.\n- **Confirm New Password** — retype the new password exactly. If the two do not match, an inline warning appears and the Change Password button stays disabled.\n\nWhen all three are valid, click **Change Password**. On success the form clears and a confirmation appears. If the server reports your current password was incorrect, nothing changes and you can try again — the new password is never applied unless the current one checks out.\n\n**Tips:**\n- Changing your password does not sign you out of QB Engineer on the device you are using.\n- A password change does **not** touch your kiosk PIN or your MFA devices — those are separate and stay as they were.\n- If you have forgotten your current password entirely, you cannot use this card (it requires the old password). Ask an administrator to reset it.\n\n### Setting Your Kiosk PIN\n\nThe **kiosk PIN** is a short numeric code — completely separate from your password. It is the second factor on the shop-floor kiosk and clock terminals: you identify yourself by scanning your badge (RFID / NFC / barcode), then confirm it is you by entering your PIN. The PIN is never used to sign in to the browser app; it exists for the fast, gloved-hands flow on the floor.\n\nThe **Kiosk PIN** card has two fields:\n- **PIN** — **4 to 8 digits**, numbers only. Letters and symbols are not allowed.\n- **Confirm PIN** — retype the same digits. A mismatch shows an inline warning and keeps the Set PIN button disabled.\n\nClick **Set PIN** to save. Setting a new PIN overwrites any previous one immediately — there is no separate \"old PIN\" field because the PIN is paired with a badge scan, not entered on its own. If you have never set a PIN, do it before your first shift at a kiosk so you are not stuck at the terminal.\n\n**Tips:**\n- Choose a PIN that is not trivially guessable (avoid 1234 or your badge number) but that you can punch in quickly.\n- Your PIN is stored hashed — nobody, including admins, can read it back. An administrator can only **reset** it, not view it.\n- The PIN and the password are independent. Changing one never changes the other.\n\n### Which Credential Does What?\n\n| Credential | Where you use it | Format |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Password** | Browser sign-in (with your email) | 8+ characters, any mix |\n| **Kiosk PIN** | Shop-floor kiosk / clock, after a badge scan | 4–8 digits |\n| **MFA code** | Browser sign-in second step (with password) | 6-digit rotating code |\n\nKnowing the difference avoids the classic confusion of trying to type a PIN into the browser login or a password into the kiosk. Each credential has one job.","sections":[]}"""
