            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Alternative MFA Methods (SMS / Email / WebAuthn)\n\nTOTP authenticator apps are the primary, recommended MFA method, but the underlying model supports four device types. The `MfaDeviceType` enum is `Totp`, `Sms`, `Email`, `WebAuthn`, and each `UserMfaDevice` row carries only the fields relevant to its type.\n\n- **Totp** — the only method exposed through the Account > Security setup dialog today. Uses `EncryptedSecret` (the shared TOTP secret, encrypted at rest via the ASP.NET Data Protection API) to validate the rotating 6-digit code.\n- **WebAuthn** — hardware security keys (YubiKey) or platform authenticators (Windows Hello, Touch ID). Stores `CredentialId`, `PublicKey`, and `SignCount` instead of a shared secret; nothing is typed by the user.\n- **Sms** — code delivered to `PhoneNumber`. Weaker than TOTP because of SIM-swap risk; on the login challenge the target renders masked (e.g. `***-***-1234`).\n- **Email** — code delivered to `EmailAddress`, a fallback when no other method is available; masked as `j***@example.com` on the challenge.\n\nA device's `DeviceName` is optional and falls back to the `DeviceType` string in the device list. `IsVerified` must be true before a device is usable for login — an unverified device (setup abandoned before the code check) is ignored.\n\n## Device Lockout & Recovery\n\nEach `UserMfaDevice` tracks `FailedAttempts` (consecutive bad codes) and `LockedUntil` (a timestamp the device is locked out until, null when not locked). This is the per-device throttle that blunts brute-forcing a 6-digit code, and is separate from the account-level ASP.NET Identity lockout (F-051) that the password and kiosk-PIN login paths use.\n\nRecovery when you lose your authenticator:\n- **Recovery codes** — the documented path. On the login MFA challenge, choose **Use recovery code** and enter one one-time backup code.\n- **A second registered device** — if you added a backup authenticator (the **Add Device** flow), authenticate from it instead; nothing is locked out on the device that is simply unavailable.\n- **Admin reset** — when no recovery codes and no second device remain, an administrator is the last resort. Note an admin can only reset/disable, never read your secret. If your role is under an enforced MFA policy, you will be required to set MFA up again on next login.\n\n## Recovery-Code & Device Audit Fields\n\nThe recovery-code and device tables are deliberately auditable; the plaintext recovery code never persists.\n\n`MfaRecoveryCode` fields:\n- **CodeHash** — PBKDF2 hash of the code. The plaintext is shown exactly once at generation and is never stored, so it cannot be recovered, only regenerated.\n- **IsUsed** / **UsedAt** — set when a code is consumed during a recovery login; used codes are permanently spent and cannot be reused.\n- **UsedFromIp** — the IP the code was redeemed from, recorded for security review.\n\n`UserMfaDevice` audit fields: **LastUsedAt** (last successful auth, shown as MM/dd/yyyy), **FailedAttempts** / **LockedUntil** (throttle state), **IsDefault** (the device the login challenge presents first), and the `BaseAuditableEntity` `CreatedAt` / `CreatedBy`. Generating a new recovery-code set invalidates every prior code immediately — there is never more than one live set.\n\n## Kiosk PIN vs RFID / Barcode Interplay\n\nThe kiosk PIN set on the second card of Account > Security is a distinct credential from your browser password and from MFA. It is the *second* factor on the shop-floor kiosk and clock terminals: the *first* factor is a physical scan — RFID / NFC badge or barcode — resolved through a `UserScanIdentifier`. You scan to assert identity, then enter the PIN to confirm it is you.\n\n- The PIN is **4 to 8 digits, numbers only** (`SetPinValidator`: `Length(4,8)` + `^\\d+$`), stored as a PBKDF2 hash (100,000 iterations, per-PIN salt) in `PinHash` — admins can reset it but never read it.\n- There is no separate \"old PIN\" field: setting a new PIN overwrites the previous one, because a PIN is never entered on its own (it is always gated by a badge scan).\n- Kiosk PIN login is throttled by the same account-level Identity lockout as password login (F-051) — repeated wrong PINs lock the account, not just the terminal.\n- The PIN is never accepted at the browser sign-in, and the browser password/MFA code is never used at the kiosk. Each credential has exactly one surface.\n\n## Password Complexity Policy\n\nThe browser sign-in password is governed by the ASP.NET Identity options registered in `Program.cs`:\n\n- **RequiredLength = 8** (minimum 8 characters)\n- **RequireDigit = true**\n- **RequireLowercase = true**\n- **RequireUppercase = true**\n- **RequireNonAlphanumeric = false** (symbols allowed but not required)\n- **User.RequireUniqueEmail = true** (account-level, not password)\n\nThese rules apply wherever Identity validates a password — registration, admin-initiated resets, and the **Change Password** card on Account > Security. The card additionally requires the **Current Password** to be correct before any change is applied: a wrong current password is rejected server-side and the stored password is left untouched. The new password and its confirmation must match (an inline check keeps the submit button disabled until they do). A password change does not sign you out, and it never alters your kiosk PIN or MFA devices — the three credentials are independent.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded MFA training modules");
